05241nam a22007935i 9781442683754DE-B159720190708092533.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190708s2016    onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426837547 a10.3138/97814426837542doi  a(DE-B1597)465141  a(OCoLC)944177252  a(OCoLC)999368912  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aPQ4250.E5bW75 2006eb 7aLCO0000002bisacsh04a853/.0108928700aWriting to Delight :bItalian Short Stories by Nineteenth-Century Women Writers /cAntonia Arslan, Gabriella Romani. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2016] 4cÂ©2006  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aToronto Italian Studies00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction. Scenes from Nineteenth-Century Italy: Delightful Stories on Those Long, Long Winter Evenings / rRomani, Gabriella -- tChecchina's Virtue / rSerao, Matilde -- tPaolina / rNeera -- tAunt Severina / rNeera -- tThe Lady of the Evening / rNeera -- tWinter Evenings / rColombi -- tLearn a Trade for a Rainy Day / rColombi -- tDear Hope / rMarchesa Colombi -- tThe Bread of the Departed / rPercoto, Caterina -- tThe Caning / rPercoto, Caterina -- tThe Coral Necklace / rContessa Lara -- tWoes of the Middle Class / rOlper Monis, Virginia -- tScorn for Life / rSperani, Bruno -- tAfterword. Ladies, Chickens, and Queens: The Strong Voices of Italian Women Writers / rArslan, Antonia -- tBio-bibliographies of the Authors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe nineteenth century represents a crucial historical and cultural phase in the development of modern Italy. Writing to Delight provides a selection of short stories written by some of the most accomplished and acclaimed female authors of nineteenth-century Italy, made available to an English-speaking audience for the first time through this translation. The stories that make up this anthology are written in a realistic vein and describe the life and concerns of women at a time when Italy was going through major social and economic changes. Imbued with didactic aims, the authors of these stories strove to inspire and at the same time educate their public. In this regard, Writing to Delight also serves as an instrument for a critical investigation of both the cultural productions of nineteenth-century Italy and the process of formation of modern Italian identities. With the growth of the middle-classes and a more diffuse literacy among the population, women became a visible and conspicuous social force as consumers of cultural goods, such as books and newspapers. Many of the writers included in this anthology ? Matilde Serao, Marchesa Colombi, Neera, Contessa Lara ? were not only very successful writers of fiction but also worked as journalists for some of the main national newspapers of the time. They were well acquainted with their readers? tastes and expectations and made such awareness an integral part of their creative process. Their fiction thus reflects the many topics and concerns that informed the social and cultural debates of nineteenth-century Italy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aItalian fictionxWomen authorsvTranslations into English. 0aItalian fictiony19th centuryvTranslations into English. 0aShort stories, ItalianxWomen authorsvTranslations into English. 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / General.2bisacsh1 aArslan, Antonia, eeditor.1 aRomani, Gabriella, eeditor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUTP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066769108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311049095440uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/9781442683754423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/c